<!-- Async WordPress.com Remote Login -->
<script id="wpcom_remote_login_js">
var wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth = '';
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( element_id ) {
	var dom_node = document.getElementById( element_id );
	if ( dom_node ) { dom_node.remove(); }
}
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( class_name ) {
	var dom_nodes = document.querySelectorAll( '.' + class_name );
	for ( var i = 0; i < dom_nodes.length; i++ ) {
		dom_nodes[i].remove();
	}
}
function wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup() {
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( "wpcom_remote_login_msg" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_js" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_iframe" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_styles" );
}

// Watch for messages back from the remote login
window.addEventListener( "message", function( e ) {
	if ( e.origin === "https://r-login.wordpress.com" ) {
		var data = {};
		try {
			data = JSON.parse( e.data );
		} catch( e ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
			return;
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN' ) {
			// Clean up the login check iframe
			wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );

			var id_regex = new RegExp( /^[0-9]+$/ );
			var token_regex = new RegExp( /^.*|.*|.*$/ );
			if (
				token_regex.test( data.token )
				&& id_regex.test( data.wpcomid )
			) {
				// We have everything we need to ask for a login
				var script = document.createElement( "script" );
				script.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
				script.src = '/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=validate'
					+ '&wpcomid=' + data.wpcomid
					+ '&token=' + encodeURIComponent( data.token )
					+ '&host=' + window.location.protocol
						+ '//' + window.location.hostname;
				document.body.appendChild( script );
			}

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, not logged in, so redirect
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REDIRECT' ) {
			window.location = 'https://wordpress.com/log-in?redirect_to=' + window.location.href;
			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, storage access failed, remove the request
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REMOVE' ) {
			var css_zap = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 782px ) { html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } }';
			var style_zap = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style_zap.type = 'text/css';
			style_zap.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css_zap ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style_zap );

			var e = document.getElementById( 'wpcom_request_access_iframe' );
			e.parentNode.removeChild( e );

			document.cookie = 'wordpress_com_login_access=denied; path=/; max-age=31536000';

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP
		if ( data.msg === 'REQUEST_ACCESS' ) {
			console.log( 'request access: safari' );

			// Check ITP iframe enable/disable knob
			if ( wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth !== 'safari_itp_iframe' ) {
				return;
			}

			// If we are in a "private window" there is no ITP.
			var private_window = false;
			try {
				var opendb = window.openDatabase( null, null, null, null );
			} catch( e ) {
				private_window = true;
			}

			if ( private_window ) {
				console.log( 'private window' );
				return;
			}

			var iframe = document.createElement( 'iframe' );
			iframe.id = 'wpcom_request_access_iframe';
			iframe.setAttribute( 'scrolling', 'no' );
			iframe.setAttribute( 'sandbox', 'allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation' );
			iframe.src = 'https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=request_access&origin=' + encodeURIComponent( data.origin ) + '&wpcomid=' + encodeURIComponent( data.wpcomid );

			var css = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 46px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 46px !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 660px ) { html { margin-top: 71px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 71px !important; } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { display: block; height: 71px !important; } } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { border: 0px; height: 46px; position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; min-width: 100%; z-index: 99999; background: #23282d; } ';

			var style = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style.type = 'text/css';
			style.id = 'wpcom_request_access_styles';
			style.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style );

			document.body.appendChild( iframe );
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'DONE' ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
		}
	}
}, false );

// Inject the remote login iframe after the page has had a chance to load
// more critical resources
window.addEventListener( "DOMContentLoaded", function( e ) {
	var iframe = document.createElement( "iframe" );
	iframe.style.display = "none";
	iframe.setAttribute( "scrolling", "no" );
	iframe.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	iframe.src = "https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php"
		+ "?wpcom_remote_login=key"
		+ "&origin=aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGFja2xpc3RkZWNsYXNzaWZpZWQubmV0"
		+ "&wpcomid=9473618"
		+ "&time=1603821987";
	document.body.appendChild( iframe );
}, false );
</script>

		function addLoadEvent(func) {
			var oldonload = window.onload;
			if (typeof window.onload != 'function') {
				window.onload = func;
			} else {
				window.onload = function () {
					oldonload();
					func();
				}
			}
		}

<h2>üî¥ Easy-Search Season 1 Scripts</h2>
<p>&nbsp; </p>
<h3>NBC&#8217;s series <b>The Blacklist</b> created by:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b></h3>
<p>&nbsp; </p></div>
<p><span id="more-4227"></span></p>
<div align="center"><b>SERIES  STARS:</b><br />
&nbsp;<br />
Raymond &#8216;Red&#8217; Reddington ‚Äì James <b>Spader</b><br />
Elizabeth Keen ‚Äì Megan <b>Boone</b><br />
Donald Ressler ‚Äì Diego <b>Klattenhoff</b><br />
Harold Cooper ‚Äì  Harry <b>Lennix</b><br />
Tom Keen ‚Äì Ryan <b>Eggold</b><br />
Aram Mojtabai ‚Äì Amir <b>Arison</b><br />
Samar Navabi ‚Äì Mozhan <b>Marn√≤</b><br />
Dembe Zuma ‚Äì Hisham <b>Tawfiq</b><br />
&nbsp; </div>
<div align="left">
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>This is all one page,</b> meaning you can use your browser&#8217;s page search to find a <b>quote</b> you remember without knowing which episode it&#8217;s in. I use this a <i>lot.</i> Also includes full <b>lyrics</b> to main songs (at end of each episode). <b>To find beginning of major songs, search for ‚ô´</b> </p>

<h3>‚≠ï Episode 1:1 Pilot (Ranko Zamani)</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Raymond &#8220;Red&#8221; Reddington, Number Four on the FBI&#8217;s Most Wanted list and underground for 20 years, offers to turn over criminals one by one from &#8220;The Blacklist,&#8221; his personal list of under-the-radar criminal &#8220;politicians, mobsters, hackers, spies.&#8221; He has a single demand: that he speak only with Elizabeth Keen, an FBI profiler fresh out of Quantico.</i><br />
<a id="parta"></a><br />
&nbsp;</div>
<div align="center">
<p><span class="embed-youtube" style="text-align:center; display: block;"><iframe class='youtube-player' width='655' height='369' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/H1Pgng9EbtY?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent' allowfullscreen='true' style='border:0;' sandbox='allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation'></iframe></span><br />
(8:57 mins)</div>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Grey (Newton Philips): Must be good to be home again, sir.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yeah. Well, we&#8217;ll see about that.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> Good afternoon. I&#8217;m here to see Assistant Director Harold Cooper.<br />
Clerk: Do you have an appointment?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I do not. Tell him it&#8217;s Raymond Reddington.<br />
[ Red puts down his briefcase alongside the FBI seal emblazoned in the floor. He takes off his coat, folds it and places it on top of his briefcase. The receptionist has pulled up Red&#8217;s file online: &#8220;10 Most Wanted: Raymond Reddington&#8221; She quickly hits the alarm, which begins to blare loudly. Red places his hat on top of his folded jacket, then drops to his knees on the FBI seal, hands clasped behind his head, as he is quickly surrounded by armed guards with rifles aimed at his head ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: Ressler. Washington field office. I&#8217;m the case agent on Reddington.<br />
Cooper: Assistant FBI Director Cooper: When did this happen?<br />
Ressler: Under an hour ago.<br />
Cooper: We confirm it&#8217;s actually him?<br />
Ressler: It&#8217;s him all right. Prints match. Tattoos. He even volunteered classified details about a Brussels Mission in &#8217;08.<br />
Cooper: What happened in Brussels?<br />
Ressler: Sir? We tried to kill him, sir.<br />
Cooper: [ Looking at video monitor ] It really is him.<br />
Ressler: Came in with a briefcase containing every alias he&#8217;s ever used. Most of &#8217;em we&#8217;ve never even heard of.<br />
Cooper: What does he want?<br />
Ressler: Don&#8217;t know. Won&#8217;t talk. He&#8217;s a stone.<br />
Cooper: Call lab services. Have them fit him with an AlphaChip RFID tag. Assemble a full intel review. NSA. CIA.<br />
Ressler: What exactly do you want to know?<br />
Cooper: Everything.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Ressler: Raymond &#8220;Red&#8221; Reddington attended the Naval Academy. Top of his class. Graduated by the time he was 24. He was being groomed for admiral. Then in 1990, Reddington&#8217;s coming home to see his wife and his daughter for Christmas. He never arrives. This highly respected officer up and disappears from the face of the earth until four years later when classified NOFORN documents start showing up in Maghreb, Islamabad, Beijing. These leaks were traced to Reddington. This guy&#8217;s an equal opportunity offender, a facilitator of sorts, who&#8217;s built an enterprise brokering deals for fellow criminals.<br />
[ An RFID tracking chip iis injected into Red&#8217;s arm ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Ouch.<br />
Ressler: He has no country. He has no political agenda. Reddington&#8217;s only allegiance is to the highest bidder.<br />
Tech: They call him something in the papers.<br />
Cooper: &#8220;The concierge of crime.&#8221;<br />
Tech: He&#8217;s online.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Evidently someone with the authority to make decisions has arrived. I think I smell the stench of your cologne, Agent Cooper. Smells like hubris.<br />
Cooper: Get these feeds fixed. I want him up here. Come on.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You must have many questions, so let&#8217;s begin with the most important one. Why I&#8217;m here. Remember the 1986 attack on the U.S. Embassy in Damascus, the abduction of the six foreign nationals from the French consulate in Algiers in &#8217;97, or the 2002 breach of the Krungthai Bank in Bangkok? You see these events as unrelated. I can tell you one man is responsible for all three. His name is Ranko Zamani. You want him. I want him. So let&#8217;s say for the moment our interests are aligned.<br />
&nbsp;<br />

<b>Red:</b> Agent Cooper, you&#8217;ve overestimated your authority. I said I&#8217;ll help you find Zamani, and I will. But from this point forward, there&#8217;s one very important rule: I speak only with Elizabeth Keen.<br />
Ressler: Who the hell&#8217;s Elizabeth Keen? </p>

[ Liz Keen is home in bed, sleeping alongside her husband Tom. Hudson, their dog, wakes Tom ]<br />

Tom: All right. Good thinkin&#8217;.<br />
Liz We&#8217;re out of milk.<br />

Liz:  Is this pee? I&#8217;m standing in pee, babe.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

Cooper: What will they find?<br />

Cooper: They tell me today&#8217;s your first day as a profiler.<br />

Liz: Thank you.<br />
Cooper: Do me a favor. Profile yourself.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m sorry, sir?<br />
Cooper: Who are you? What is he looking for? Profile Elizabeth Keen.<br />
Liz: Oh. Okay. Uh Um, well, I&#8217;ve been with the Bureau for four years. I was the head of the Mobile Emergency Psych Unit in New York. We worked murders, extortion‚Äì<br />
Cooper: Read your r√©sum√©.<br />
Liz: Of course. My colleagues call me &#8220;sir.&#8221; They think I&#8217;m a bitch. Like most kids who raised themselves, I can display narcissistic behavior. I can be withdrawn, disconnected. Uh, I have a deep yearning to understand and relate to the criminal mind. I&#8217;m board certified in forensic psychology, and yet I operate under the delusion that I can rewrite my past by having kids of my own.<br />
Cooper: Do you find it odd Reddington surrendered himself the day you started working as a profiler?<br />
Liz: I think that it suggests he was waiting for me.<br />
Cooper: Why you? Specifically.<br />
Liz: Because I&#8217;m new and he thinks I can be easily manipulated. The man obviously doesn&#8217;t know me very well.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Liz: What is this place?<br />
Ressler: D.C. Metro Sorting Facility, U.S. Postal Service. It was abandoned and slated for demo twelve years ago. The Bureau acquired the building post‚Äì9/11. Been operating a variety of covert operations here ever since.<br />
Liz: So this is a black site?<br />
Ressler:  We&#8217;re sentimental. We prefer to call it The Post Office.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: [ To Liz ] If you need anything, remember we&#8217;re right here.<br />
[ Liz walks down from observation deck to floor of facility. A chair awaits her. Reddington is cuffed (wrists and ankles) to a chair inside a containment unit (the &#8216;orange box&#8217;), bullet and blast-resistant, designed to prevent ingress or egress. The door of the unit swings slowly outward, then the unit is pulled clanking backwards, leaving only the platform which forms the floor of the unit with the cuffed Reddington ]<br />

<b>Red:</b> Agent Keen, what a pleasure.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: Who is the Ukrainian?<br />

Ressler: We have our own list.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Agent Ressler, please. We all know your Top Ten is little more than a publicity campaign. It&#8217;s a popularity contest at best. I&#8217;m talking about the criminals who matter. The ones you can&#8217;t find because you don&#8217;t even know they exist. Zamani was a small fish. I&#8217;m Ahab. And if you want the whales on my list, you have to play by my rules. I never sleep in the same location for more than two nights in a row. I want a fully encrypted 8-millimeter tag embedded in my neck not that garbage from AlphaChip you stuck in my shoulder. I want my own security I&#8217;ve compiled a list of five acceptable applicants. Pick two. Whatever I tell you falls under an immunity package that I negotiate myself. And finally, most importantly, I speak only with Elizabeth Keen.</p>

‚ô™ <b>Lyrics to Citizens</b><br />
By Alice Russell</p>
<p>Citizens of planet earth don&#8217;t get caught in the act<br />

<h3>Episode 1:5 The Courier</h3>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> The Courier guarantees the of delivery of high value assets by assuring the deaths of both sender and receiver if either fails in their part of the transaction. </i> </p>

<p>Liz: What is this place?<br />

<h3>Episode 1:7 Frederick Barnes</h3>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> Frederick Barnes loves his son, who is stricken with a rare genetic condition. With research dollars non-existent, Barnes will use the public as his trial subjects. Plus: superbubble baby.</i> </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Recording: ] Connecting trains to the orange and blue line at Farragut Street.<br />
Woman: Bergman&#8217;s, right? The store where you bought your hat.<br />
Man: Oh, yeah. I didn&#8217;t I didn&#8217;t leave the tag on, did I?<br />

<h3>Episode 1:9 Anslo Garrick</h3>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> Anslo Garrick seeks revenge against Red for once putting a bullet in his head at point blank range. But greater forces lie in wait, as a mysterious interloper states his concerns. A key two-parter.</i> </p>

<h3>Episode 1:13 The Cyprus Agency</h3>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> The Cyprus Adoption Agency promises to deliver the perfect newborn to would-be parents. But no records can be found of where or how the agency obtains the newborns. Plus: Red finds the mole.</i> </p>

<p>[ Suddenly Dr Mallory springs on Liz. They fight for her gun. Mallory gets the gun after he pushes one of the sedated women on top of Liz. Mallory shoots ‚Äì not at Liz, however, but at Ressler who has appeared. Mallory misses but Ressler shoots and wounds Mallory ]</p>
<p>Ressler: Keen.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;m okay. Call it in. [ She checks the woman Mallory had thrown on her ]</p>
<p>[ Cooper arrives at the scene ]<br />
Cooper: Twenty-two women including Charlotte Patterson, the girl we lost at Georgetown. Allison Hayes and Michelle Lefferts‚Äì we got them all.<br />
Liz: Except Kate Ellison.<br />
Cooper: You solved all those missing-persons reports in one case. And the mothers of every one of those 27 kids have been accounted for.<br />
Young doctor: [ To Cooper ] Sir, there&#8217;s a complete IVF laboratory. The women&#8217;s eggs were surgically retrieved, fertilized here, and then re‚Äìtransferred. It&#8217;s all state‚Äìof‚Äìthe‚Äìart. The genetic testing is cutting-edge. It&#8217;s remarkable. Some of the charts go back years.</p>
<p>[ Liz is interrogating Mallory ]<br />
Liz: We found Kate Ellison. [ The body found by the dog in the park ] And I&#8217;m guessing that&#8217;s not the only body we&#8217;ll find before this is done. Is it Michael? We know who you are. Michael Shaw adopted at 7 by Charles and Jill Lassiter and returned to foster care. Owen Mallory has no record, but Michael Shaw‚Äì he&#8217;s quite a con man, isn&#8217;t he?<br />
Mallory/Shaw: Thank you.<br />
Liz: You must have felt so rejected, being removed‚Äì<br />
Mallory/Shaw: I wasn&#8217;t removed. I was returned like a defective toy.<br />
Liz: I met the Lassiters. Is that why you did this? To get back at them?<br />
Mallory/Shaw: The Lassiters didn&#8217;t want a child. They wanted an accessory to smile for their Christmas card. They wanted perfection, like all the others. So I sell what people want. Everybody wins. They get their little geniuses, and‚Äì<br />
Liz: And you and your employees get rich?<br />
Mallory/Shaw: No. Well, yes. But it&#8217;s not about the money for me.<br />
Liz: What does that mean?<br />
Mallory/Shaw: I think I&#8217;ve said enough. But my legacy is complete. And there is nothing you can do to change that.<br />
Liz: Your legacy. You&#8217;re the father. The children brokered by the Cyprus Agency are yours. Why? Mallory/Shaw: Well, I was damaged goods, wasn&#8217;t I? Not fit to survive in their privileged world. Well, I am surviving. Now part of me is thriving in every home that has my child.</p>
<p>[ Footsteps ] [ Telephone ringing ] [ Door opens ] [ Door closes ]<br />
Tom: Honey? What&#8217;s wrong? Are you okay?<br />
Liz: I can&#8217;t do it.<br />
Tom: Do what?<br />
Liz: You&#8217;re not ready. We&#8217;re not ready.<br />
Tom: No, look‚Äì you don&#8217;t have to take any time off, all right? Just‚Äì there&#8217;s a lot of working moms out there, and you can do both.<br />
Liz: No.<br />
Tom: You can do both.<br />
Liz: Tom it&#8217;s us. [ Voice breaking ] It&#8217;s us. I don&#8217;t know what&#8217;s wrong. I don&#8217;t understand it, but something&#8217;s not right. I can&#8217;t have a baby right now.<br />
Tom: Well, I don&#8217;t know what to say to that.<br />
[ Sniffles ] [ Inhales sharply ] [ Voice breaking ]<br />
Liz: Honey, you can&#8217;t tell me that there&#8217;s not one shred of doubt, one shred that wonders if this is broken.<br />

<h3>Episode 1:15 The Judge</h3>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> When the wheels of the justice system fail to deliver justice, what recourse do the victims or those falsely condemned have? The Judge offers a final appeal.</i> </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ A man walks down a highway on a cold winter&#8217;s day. His gait is staggering, his gaze empty. He carries a tattered paper sack ]<br />
[ Wind whistling ] [ A semi-trailer truck thunders by, horn blaring ]<br />
[ A smaller truck slows and its driver rolls down the window ]<br />
Driver: Hey. Hey, pal.<br />
[ Brakes screech ] [ He gets out and goes over to the man, who is bearded and unresponsive ]<br />

Assistant US Attorney? </p>
<p>Highway patrol: He hasn&#8217;t spoken. The doctor said he experienced severe trauma.<br />

<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t want you to find her. I know where she is. I want you to tell me where she&#8217;s been. Cities, safe houses, aliases. She&#8217;s already faked her death to elude me. Now she&#8217;s back. I want you to tell me everything you can about where she&#8217;s been, what she&#8217;s been up to.</p>
<p>[ At a conference for teachers Tom is attending ]<br />

<p><b>Red:</b> [ Door closes ] Lizzy. Have you seen the paper?<br />
Liz: What about it?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mark Hastings, US Attorney from Maryland ‚Äì the head of the Reynoso Cartel.<br />
A week later, he went missing.<br />

Liz: <b>Red:</b> Yeah, well, two days ago, he was found wandering on a road in Pennsylvania. Nobody knows where he&#8217;s been.<br />
Liz: Was he in hiding?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I believe he was held captive, but not by the Reynoso cartel. It&#8217;s all quite a mystery. They say he&#8217;s too traumatized to speak. But if what I believe about Hastings is true, if he has been held captive all these years, then it would confirm that the myth is true ‚Äì The Judge is real.<br />
Liz: The Judge?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Every culture has a justice myth, an avenging angel who exacts retribution for the weak and innocent. Golem for the Jews, Tu Po for the Chinese. The Ancient Greeks had Adrestia, the Goddess Of Revenge.<br />
Liz: And we have The Judge.<br />
Think of him as a prisoner&#8217;s court of last resort. When your legal appeals have all been exhausted and there is no hope left, you can make one last plea to The Judge.<br />
Liz: What kind of plea?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Prisoners can state their case, argue their innocence, explain why they were convicted unfairly and who is responsible ‚Äì a prosecutor, a corrupt detective, maybe an incompetent public defender.<br />
This demand for justice ‚Äì where does it go?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Supposedly, it&#8217;s passed among inmates until it finally reaches some book depository at the FederalPenitentiary in  Monroe, Virginia.<br />
And then?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Nobody knows for sure. Nobody&#8217;s ever met him. Somehow, the appeals make their way to The Judge. He reviews the case, and if he thinks you&#8217;re innocent, he evens the score. If freedom or life were taken unfairly, he demands the same in return ‚Äì an eye for an eye.</p>
<p>Cooper: Reddington says Mark Hastings was held captive?<br />

<p>Cooper: Tom.<br />

<h3>Episode 1:17 Ivan </h3>
<p><i><b>Blurb:</b> A famous hacker, Ivan, is blamed for gaining access to a super-secret government project which allows a single interface to disable an entire city. But Ivan says it&#8217;s not him. Then, who? Plus, the Sorrento music box.</i> </p>

Ressler: Alexei Fayer, Bogdan Chrikoff, and Vadim Okecka.<br />
Liz: One of them has to be Berlin.<br />
Cooper: Talk to that surviving guard. Bring photos of our fugitives. Nobody sleeps until Agent Malik&#8217;s killer is found.</p>
<p>Cooper: Agent Keen. Found it in Evidence [ Gives her toy bracelet Beth gave her in Pilot ], from that first day.<br />
[ Flashback] Liz: Oh. You don&#8217;t have to‚Äì Thank you so much. This is beautiful. Wow. [ End ]<br />
Cooper: Thought it might remind you of all the good we&#8217;ve done.</p>
<p>[ Ressler shows photos of men to man in hospital, later identified as Berlin ]<br />
(Berlin): No. No, no, no, no, no, no.<br />
Ressler: Look, we know the situation you&#8217;re in. The people you work for ‚Äì they know you&#8217;re here, so whatever secret you&#8217;re trying to protect‚Äì<br />
Liz: We know about the man they call &#8220;Berlin.&#8221; We know he&#8217;s one of those three, and we need you to tell us which one.<br />
(Berlin): You don&#8217;t know who you&#8217;re dealing with.<br />
Liz: Why don&#8217;t you tell us?<br />
(Berlin): I don&#8217;t know his name. No one knows his name. All I know is the story.<br />
Ressler: Story? What story?<br />
(Berlin): They say he started in the Red Army and then the KGB, and he was notorious for sending off his enemies to the war camps in Siberia. Then, towards the end of the Cold War, some stories began to circulate that his daughter had fallen in love with a dissident. She was captured, imprisoned. But, you see, the Colonel ‚Äì he knew his way around. He arranged so she could escape.[?] When the Kremlin found out, they decided to make an example of him, so they sent him off to Siberia to rot away with his enemies. It is said that they could hear him every night praying for his daughter&#8217;s safety, that she would never be found. And one day, something arrived in his cell. It was a pocket watch he had given his daughter, and inside was a picture of her.‚ô§ And a few months later, something else arrived‚Äì her ear. And then a finger. His enemies sent her back to him piece by piece. No one knows how he did it, but he did‚Äì some say that he carved a knife from one of his daughter&#8217;s bones‚Äì and slaughtered all the men that had held him captive for so many years. Then he vanished, disappeared. A ghost hunting, searching for the man responsible for his daughter&#8217;s death.The man you&#8217;re looking for is not on those photos. The man you&#8217;re looking for was never on the manifest.<br />
<i>[[ Note: ( ‚ùó Spoiler ‚ùó ) This version differs from Berlin&#8217;s story later. It says Berlin helped his daughter escape, but she was caught. In 2:8 The Decembrist, Zoe accuses her father of imprisoning her friends and that she was trying to escape from him. It was Fitch et al who helped her escape. ]]</i></p>
<p>Martin: One of the most wanted men in the world has escaped federal custody. There are prisoners running free in the city. A CIA agent has been murdered. Where are you on the case? Cooper: We&#8217;ve got the plane&#8217;s manifest. Unfortunately, our POI&#8217;s not on it.<br />
Martin: So you&#8217;re nowhere?<br />
Cooper: We&#8217;re piecing it together.<br />
Martin: The good news is that Reddington&#8217;s escape from federal custody has been contained, which means if Keen is willing, the task force can continue.<br />

<p>Ressler: We have an eyewitness. You were picked up six blocks from the crime scene.<br />
We have a bloody fingerprint inside the vehicle, surveillance from that club. You have one chance right now‚Äì who commissioned the hits? I want a name and location. Okay. All right. Funny thing, you know‚Äì I used to be a real Boy Scout, strictly by the book, followed all the rules. Then this thing happens. My fianc√©, she gets killed‚Äì murdered right in front of me. The guy I did it‚Äì the only way I could get him was to forget all the rules. It was a real crossroads for me. Had to choose which path to take. The thing is, I think it&#8217;s real important for you to know ‚Äì the path I took there wasn&#8217;t any rules. And the thing I realized was that sometimes, that&#8217;s okay. Like when some greasy Russian starts murdering my friends! I want a name. I want a name! I want a name. </p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Milos Pavel Kinsky ‚Äì sometimes known as &#8220;Berlin.&#8221; He&#8217;s a Russian national, former Spetsnaz Commando, trained in the KGB&#8217;s 45 Division. Organized crime is now his fancy.<br />
Fitch: Makes Putin look like a Christmas elf. Now that you know who he is, what exactly did you do to put him in such a bad mood?<br />

Fitch: And you&#8217;re here because you want?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Access. The kind even the FBI doesn&#8217;t have. All those spinning satellites that record every keystroke, every phone call, everybody&#8217;s dirty little secrets. You find him for me, and I&#8217;ll do the rest.<br />
Fitch: I heard about Harold.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Find him.</p>
<p>Liz: They don&#8217;t know if Cooper&#8217;s gonna make it through the night. You still haven&#8217;t told me how Sam was involved in this.<br />

The friend told Sam he was leaving town, that he was in danger and that he needed someone to care for a little girl that her father had died that night in a fire. So Sam took the little girl in, and he raised her as his own always sheltering her from the truth about her biological father.<br />
Liz: And that&#8217;s why you killed him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I killed Sam because he was in pain and he wanted to die and because I had to protect you from the truth.‚ô§<br />

But I did it to keep you from learning the name of your real father, to protect you. And you must understand ‚Äì having done that, I&#8217;m certainly not going to tell you who he was now.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Yes?<br />

<p><b>Red:</b> I must say, I&#8217;m very good at finding people. I&#8217;ve tracked enemies far and wide. I once found a hedge‚Äìfund manager hiding in the Amazon with the Yawalapiti on the banks of the Kuluene River. You know what the key to finding your enemies is? Remembering everyone&#8217;s name. It&#8217;s critical to my survival. Anyone knows the head of some drug cartel in Colombia, some politician in Paris. But I know their wives, girlfriends, children, their enemies, their friends. I know their favorite bartender, their butcher. I remember the name of the baker I stole the strawberry bismark from when I was 11 years old and his wife‚ÄìTrudy Svoboda. But you‚Äì I have no idea who in the Sam Hill you are. I have not a clue what I&#8217;ve done to you, what I&#8217;ve taken from you. And yet, of all the people I&#8217;ve hurt, none of them have come after me with half as much vim and vigor as you. I don&#8217;t even recognize your face. I&#8217;m stymied. And yet, here we are. You found me.<br />
Kinsky [ aka Fake-Berlin ]: Through your weakness. I searched for one for years‚Äì a weakness that would allow me to get to you. I nearly gave up. And then I find out about her. Seemed so implausible that someone so careful could be so careless. And so I exploited it and waited. And here we are thanks to Elizabeth Keen.</p>
<p>[ Tom gets in car that Liz is in. Points gun at her ]<br />
Tom: Hey, babe.</p>
<p><b>Red:</b> Help me understand what horrible thing I did to you that could possibly make all of this worth it. Who on God&#8217;s green Earth are you? What was that? Being shot in the hand is just an absolute bitch‚Äì all those little bones. At least it goes right through. Worst part, honestly, is needing somebody to help zip your fly. Tell me your story. I&#8217;m not leaving here without a story. Being shot in the hip, on the other hand‚Äì Jiminy Cricket. Thick bone, large artery not to mention the fact that it makes walking upright forever impossible. Just don&#8217;t pass out. Stay focused. The story. What did I do to you? How about the kneecap? The IRA always loved a good kneecapping.<br />
Kinsky: Beirut! Beirut.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The Campolongo Incident.<br />
[ Tom enters room, with Liz in front of him, holding gun to her head ]<br />
Tom: Slide it. Slide the gun now.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. Are you hurt?<br />
Kinsky: Do it! Kill her! Pull the trigger! Do it! Now! Kill her! Pull the trigger! Do it now!<br />
Liz: Don&#8217;t do it. Do you hear me?! ‚Äì Tom. Please.<br />

[ Red shoots Kinsky/Fake-Berlin in head ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Well, that simplifies matters. Just the three of us. [ Red stretches arms out, pointing his gun away from Tom, begins walking toward him ] Tom, put the gun down before you do something you&#8217;ll deeply regret. I&#8217;m the one you want. Make the right choice, Tom. But make it fast. Because when I get over there, I&#8217;m gonna take that gun away from you. [Tom shoots at Red, but Liz&#8217;s hair obstructs his shot, and he only nicks Red&#8217;s shoulder, Red flinches. Liz Turns and struggles with Tom for his gun. She gets it and shoots Tom three times in the abdomen. He slumps down wall to floor. Red quickly approaches Tom, is about to shoot him.]<br />
Liz: [ Grabs Red&#8217;s arm ] No!<br />

Liz: Please go. I&#8217;ll finish it. This is between us.<br />

1. Tom threatens Liz in order to get to Red (and hides behind her to protect himself)<br />

4. Tom shoots but his gun is tangled in Liz&#8217;s hair and his aim is off<br />
5. Red flinches from a shot to his shoulder<br />
6. Liz wrestles with Tom for the gun, gets it, shoots him once. Tom goes for the gun; Liz shoots him two more times<br />
7. Red comes over to finish Tom off<br />
8. Liz stops Red, saying she will take care of killing Tom

<h3>‚ô´ Just Breathe</h3>

<p>Stay with me<br />
You&#8217;re all I see&#8230;</p>
<p>‚ô™ Did I say that I need you?<br />
Did I say that I want you?<br />
Oh, if I didn&#8217;t I&#8217;m a fool you see<br />
No one knows this more than me</p>
<p>‚ô™ As I come clean&#8230;<br />
I wonder everyday, as I look upon your face, uh-huh<br />
Everything you gave<br />
And nothing you would save, oh no</p>
<p>Nothing you would take<br />
Everything you gave&#8230;</p>
<p>‚ô™ Did I say that I need you?<br />
Oh, did I say that I want you?<br />
Oh, if I didn&#8217;t I&#8217;m a fool you see<br />
No one knows this more than me<br />
And I come clean, ah&#8230;</p>
<p>‚ô™ Nothing you would take<br />
Everything you gave<br />
Hold me til I die<br />
Meet you on the other side&#8230;</p>

YouTube: <a href="http://bit.ly/1IgKCER" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1IgKCER</a>
</p></blockquote>
<p>END 1:22 ‚ùå‚ùå‚ùå</p>
<h2 id="finis"><i>FINIS </i></h2>
